huntBios.GENERAL_INFORMATION: This hunt unit encompasses low elevation desert and higher mountainous sagebrush terrain, with the pronghorn distributed throughout the unit.  Road access is good throughout the unit, with one area-Bare Top-closed to motorized vehicles.  There is a migration study occurring to look at winter habitat use; it's asked that collared animals not be harvested if possible.
huntBios.SAFETY_CONS:
Due to recent storms, several roads in the 3 Corners vicinity have washed out and are impassable to any vehicle, including side by sides and ATVs. Please do not harm the habitat by trying to drive off road around wash outs. Driving off road is illegal.

Cellular phone coverage is spotty on this hunt unit. Satellite phones do work in the area. A "Spot Tracker" type of satellite messaging device for safety can be used if you decide to camp in an area without cell phone service and do not wish to drive to reach service. Make sure someone knows where you plan to camp and when you will return.

Camps should be kept clean to prevent bear incidents. Food should be kept inside vehicles or bear-proof containers. Coolers are not bear-proof. Bears have gotten into camps in the past. Number and severity of bear incidents differ by year depending on weather and other food availability. Meat and garbage should be put away inside a vehicle or hung in a tree above 8 feet off the ground and 3 feet away from the trunk or any branches of the tree.
huntBios.WEATHER_CONS: The weather on this hunt unit can vary dramatically between the hunting seasons. Be prepared for rain, lightning, snow, wind and heat. It is quite common on clear mornings for clouds to build through the morning and have thunderstorms in the afternoon. Be very cautious of lightning while hunting on high ridges or exposed slopes. Early fall snow storms occur occasionally in this area. Most years the snow will melt off within a day or two until through the first week of October.

huntBios.BIOLOGIST_NOTES:
Scouting Tips:
Pronghorn are fairly habitual and can be found in the same general area from late summer through the hunt. Pronghorn are best scouted from a distance using a spotting scope or binoculars so they don’t leave the area. They are most active in the morning and evening when the temperatures are cooler; these are the best times to scout.

Behavior:
Like other wildlife, they are most active in the early mornings and evenings, but they can be up and moving any time of the day. Most of the time they are in desert scrub/sagebrush flat areas. If the weather is extremely hot, they will often seek shade during the middle part of the day. Pronghorn are herd animals. You will often see groups of does and fawns with only a few bucks mixed in during the fall. During the rut, bucks will separate from other males to find does to mate with. The rest of the year, the bucks are usually with other pronghorn.

Buck vs Doe:
Hunters can tell bucks from does by several characteristics. Bucks will have larger horns and a black cheek patch.

Pronghorn rut:
The pronghorn rut usually starts the end of September so it does not really affect the hunt.

Where to find pronghorn:
90% of the pronghorn are found on public lands in desert scrub and sagebrush flat areas. They typically stay out of heavily treed and cliffy areas. Pronghorn are found near water sources.

Recommended areas in the Three Corners/West Daggett:
Good areas to hunt include Clay Basin, Goslin Mountain, Antelope Flat, Bare Top, and Lucerne Valley. Very few pronghorn are found in Browns Park.

huntMaster.HARVEST_REPORTING: REQUIRED: click here or call 1-800-221-0659 to report your harvest. You must report your harvest, even if you did not take an animal, within 30 days of the season end date that is printed on your permit; failure to do so may result in you not being able to apply for big game species in subsequent years. Submitting teeth or other biological samples from your animal, or having your animal checked by a DWR representative or CWMU operator does NOT fulfill your mandatory harvest reporting requirement.

huntBoundaryInfos.LAND_OWNERSHIP: 90% Public Land - US Forest Service and BLM lands.
huntBoundaryInfos.CAMPGRND_INFO:
All Campgrounds on this unit are managed by the US Forest Service and BLM. Camping outside of official campgrounds is also permitted on most of the public lands. Please direct all questions regarding campground availability and other camping questions to the US Forest Service. Maps and camping regulations are available on their websites.
Ashley National Forest: http://www.fs.usda.gov/main/ashley/home
Uinta-Wasatch-Cache National Forest: http://www.fs.usda.gov/main/uwcnf/
huntBoundaryInfos.COUNTY_ROAD_INFO: County Road Access information: http://www.daggettcounty.org/index.aspx?nid=17 and http://www.utahcommuterlink.com/
huntBoundaryInfos.ATV_VEH_ACCESS:
Most roads and ATV trails on this unit are managed by the US Forest Service or BLM and are covered on their Travel Management Plans. Please direct all questions regarding which roads and trails ATVs can be operated on to the US Forest Service. There is no vehicle access allowed on Baretop.
Ashley National Forest: http://www.fs.usda.gov/detail/ashley/home/?cid=STELPRDB5432815
Uinta-Wasatch-Cache National Forest: http://www.fs.usda.gov
BLM: http://www.blm.gov/ut/st/en/fo/vernal.html
Most areas are closed to off road vehicle use except on designated routes.
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIV_TRIBE_LAND_ISSUES: The boundary of this hunt unit does not include Tribal Trust Lands and does not have much private land included.  Hunters should receive written permission from private landowners prior to the start of the hunts if they wish to hunt private property.
huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: Daggett and Summit counties—Boundary begins at the Utah-Wyoming-Colorado state line (Three Corners); south on the Utah-Colorado state line to the Green River; west along the Green River to Flaming Gorge Reservoir; west along the south shoreline of Flaming Gorge Reservoir to Cart Creek; south along this creek to US-191; south on US-191 to the Uintah/Daggett county line (summit of the Uinta Mountains); west along this summit to the head of Burnt Fork drainage (Divide Pass/Island Lake); north along the Burnt Fork drainage bottom and Burnt Fork Creek to the Utah-Wyoming state line; east on this state line to the Utah-Wyoming-Colorado state line (Three Corners). USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Dutch John, Kings Peak.  Boundary questions?  Call the Vernal office, 435-781-9453.
